Average Metric: 12.10 / 14 (86.4%):  81%|████████▏ | 13/16 [01:16<00:11,  3.90s/it]Average Metric: 12.10 / 14 (86.4%):  88%|████████▊ | 14/16 [01:16<00:07,  3.74s/it]Question: My spouse earns income from freelance consulting and also receives a
  pension. How do I assess whether her total income falls under the
  threshold for me to remain entitled to the household allowance?
Example answer: The household allowance is payable only where the gross annual income
  of the member of staff's spouse or recognised partner does not
  exceed EUR 71,764. For this purpose, "gross annual income" is
  defined as income originating in the calendar year preceding that in
  respect of which eligibility is assessed, from employment or self-
  employment, from income replacement (e.g. maternity allowance,
  parental allowance, social security benefits and unemployment
  allowance, but not payments representing reimbursement of expenses),
  or from a pension, before tax and before the deduction of social
  security contributions; investment income and income from capital
  gains are not considered. Both the freelance consulting income and
  the pension would therefore count toward the threshold. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, page 9; ECB Staff Rules, page 63)
Predicted answer: You remain entitled only if your spouse’s gross annual income does not
  exceed EUR 71,764. Key points for assessment: - What counts: include
  income from freelance consulting (self‑employment) and income from a
  pension; these are counted as “gross annual income” (before tax and
  before deduction of social‑security contributions). Exclude
  investment income or capital gains. (ECB Staff Rules, 3.5.1, p.63;
  Conditions of Employment, p.9)   - Measurement period: use income
  originating in the calendar year preceding the year for which
  eligibility is assessed. (ECB Staff Rules, 3.5.1, p.63)   - Evidence
  required: provide documentary proof (for example, the latest tax
  declaration and salary statement, or other documents the ECB
  accepts) to the ECB prior to payment. (ECB Staff Rules, 3.5.2;
  3.3.1, p.63)   - If both partners are ECB staff and both earn less
  than EUR 71,764, the household allowance is paid to the partner with
  the higher salary. (ECB Staff Rules, 3.5.4, p.63)   - Minimum
  allowance: the household allowance shall not be less than EUR 345
  per month. (Conditions of Employment, p.9)  (ECB Staff Rules, pp.63;
  Conditions of Employment, p.9)
