Question: I'm approaching the end of my ECB contract and have been notified that
  a cooling-off period applies, which prevents me from taking up the
  new role I had lined up. What financial support is available during
  that period?
Example answer: Certain staff intending to engage in a new occupational activity after
  the end of their ECB employment must refrain, for a specified
  cooling-off period, from any activity that could conflict with the
  ECB's interests. Staff who are prohibited as a result of that
  cooling-off period from undertaking a specific activity and who
  cannot find a suitable alternative and are consequently unemployed
  are entitled, for the duration of the prohibition, to a special
  monthly allowance of 80% of the last basic salary for the first year
  and 60% for the year thereafter, household and child allowances,
  continued cover under the ECB health, long-term care and accident
  insurance (subject to contributions), an education allowance capped
  at EUR 393 per month (or EUR 764 for certified imperative
  educational needs), and accrual of pensionable service. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, pages 3, 18–19)
Predicted answer: Main entitlement: If you are prohibited by a cooling‑off period and
  remain unemployed because you cannot take up the proposed activity,
  you are entitled to unemployment‑related benefits for the duration
  of the prohibition and while unemployed. (ECB Conditions of
  Employment, p.18)  Key elements and conditions: - Eligibility:
  applies to members of staff who, following end of employment, are
  prohibited by a cooling‑off period from taking up a specific
  occupational activity and are unemployed as a result (Conditions of
  Employment, p.18).   - Monthly unemployment allowance: 60% of your
  last basic salary for six months; thereafter 30% of your last basic
  salary for the subsequent six months and any additional months in
  relation to years of service and age (Conditions of Employment,
  p.17).   - Allowances and insurance: entitlement to household and
  child allowances; continued cover under the ECB health insurance,
  long‑term care insurance and accident insurance scheme, subject to
  payment of the relevant contributions (Conditions of Employment,
  p.17).   - Education allowance: reimbursement up to EUR 393 per
  month (increased to EUR 764 per month for children with certified,
  imperative educational needs); payable only until the end of the
  academic year in which you become unemployed and subject to the
  stated conditions (Conditions of Employment, p.17).   - One‑off
  service payment: a one‑off payment equal to one month’s salary at
  Band A, step 1 for each full year of service upon providing evidence
  of registration as unemployed and seeking employment through the
  competent employment authorities; the payment shall be at least the
  equivalent of three months’ salary at Band A, step 1 and shall not
  exceed the equivalent of twelve months’ salary at Band A, step 1
  (Conditions of Employment, p.18).   - Offsets: benefits of the same
