Question: My spouse earns income from freelance consulting and also receives a
  pension. How do I assess whether her total income falls under the
  threshold for me to remain entitled to the household allowance?
Example answer: The household allowance is payable only where the gross annual income
  of the member of staff's spouse or recognised partner does not
  exceed EUR 71,764. For this purpose, "gross annual income" is
  defined as income originating in the calendar year preceding that in
  respect of which eligibility is assessed, from employment or self-
  employment, from income replacement (e.g. maternity allowance,
  parental allowance, social security benefits and unemployment
  allowance, but not payments representing reimbursement of expenses),
  or from a pension, before tax and before the deduction of social
  security contributions; investment income and income from capital
  gains are not considered. Both the freelance consulting income and
  the pension would therefore count toward the threshold. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, page 9; ECB Staff Rules, page 63)
Predicted answer: You remain entitled to the household allowance only if your spouse’s
  gross annual income for the relevant calendar year does not exceed
  EUR 71,764. To assess this: (1) add together her income from
  freelance consulting (self‑employment) and her pension for the
  calendar year preceding the year for which entitlement is assessed;
  (2) use amounts before tax and before deduction of social security
  contributions; (3) exclude investment income or capital gains.
  Provide evidence (e.g. latest tax declaration and salary/statement)
  as required. The household‑allowance threshold is EUR 71,764 and the
  allowance shall not be less than EUR 345 per month. (ECB Staff
  Rules, p.63; ECB Conditions of Employment, p.9)
