Question: Up to what age is a child considered a dependent child for the
  purposes of the child allowance?
Example answer: To qualify as a dependent child, the child must be under 26 years of
  age, must reside in the member of staff’s household or be
  financially supported by the member of staff, must not receive a
  gross annual income above the prescribed threshold in the current
  calendar year, must not be on military or alternative service, and
  must not be married or in a registered partnership. (ECB Staff
  Rules, pages 63–64)
Predicted answer: A child is considered a dependent child for child-allowance purposes
  until they are aged under twenty-six.   1. If the dependent child
  must do compulsory military or alternative service before reaching
  age 26, the age limit is extended by the duration of that service.
  2. Children suffering from a serious illness or disability may
  receive special treatment under the Staff Rules; the child allowance
  may be doubled for under‑26s and may be granted or extended beyond
  age 26 in accordance with the conditions set out in the Staff Rules
  and Conditions of Employment. (ECB Conditions of Employment, Art.16,
  p.9; ECB Staff Rules, §§3.6.1–3.6.4, pp.63–64)
