Question: I'm approaching the end of my ECB contract and have been notified that
  a cooling-off period applies, which prevents me from taking up the
  new role I had lined up. What financial support is available during
  that period?
Example answer: Certain staff intending to engage in a new occupational activity after
  the end of their ECB employment must refrain, for a specified
  cooling-off period, from any activity that could conflict with the
  ECB's interests. Staff who are prohibited as a result of that
  cooling-off period from undertaking a specific activity and who
  cannot find a suitable alternative and are consequently unemployed
  are entitled, for the duration of the prohibition, to a special
  monthly allowance of 80% of the last basic salary for the first year
  and 60% for the year thereafter, household and child allowances,
  continued cover under the ECB health, long-term care and accident
  insurance (subject to contributions), an education allowance capped
  at EUR 393 per month (or EUR 764 for certified imperative
  educational needs), and accrual of pensionable service. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, pages 3, 18–19)
Predicted answer: Main entitlement: Members of staff who, as a result of a cooling-off
  period, are prohibited from taking up a specific occupational
  activity and cannot find a suitable alternative and are therefore
  unemployed are entitled to benefits for the duration of the
  prohibition and as long as they remain unemployed.   1. Monthly
  unemployment allowance: 60% of the member’s last basic salary for
  six months; then 30% of the last basic salary for the subsequent six
  months and additional months in relation to years of service and
  age.   2. Household and child allowances.   3. Continued cover under
  the ECB health insurance, long-term care insurance and accident
  insurance scheme, subject to payment of the relevant contributions.
  4. Education allowance: reimbursement up to a maximum of EUR 393 per
  month (increased to a maximum of EUR 764 for children with
  certified, imperative educational needs). The education allowance is
  payable only until the end of the academic year in which the member
  becomes unemployed and provided the child remains.   5. Duration:
  these benefits are payable for the duration of the prohibition on
  undertaking the activity and as long as the former member remains
  unemployed. The cooling-off periods themselves are set out in the
  Staff Rules (see ECB Staff Rules, p.9).    (ECB Conditions of
  Employment, p.18; ECB Conditions of Employment, p.17; ECB Staff
  Rules, p.9)
