Question: My spouse earns income from freelance consulting and also receives a
  pension. How do I assess whether her total income falls under the
  threshold for me to remain entitled to the household allowance?
Example answer: The household allowance is payable only where the gross annual income
  of the member of staff's spouse or recognised partner does not
  exceed EUR 71,764. For this purpose, "gross annual income" is
  defined as income originating in the calendar year preceding that in
  respect of which eligibility is assessed, from employment or self-
  employment, from income replacement (e.g. maternity allowance,
  parental allowance, social security benefits and unemployment
  allowance, but not payments representing reimbursement of expenses),
  or from a pension, before tax and before the deduction of social
  security contributions; investment income and income from capital
  gains are not considered. Both the freelance consulting income and
  the pension would therefore count toward the threshold. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, page 9; ECB Staff Rules, page 63)
Predicted answer: 1. Main rule: The household allowance is payable only if the gross
  annual income of the spouse or recognised partner does not exceed
  EUR 71,764. (ECB Conditions of Employment, p.9)  2. What to include
  in the spouse’s gross annual income for the test:    - Include
  freelance consulting income (self‑employment) and any pension; both
  count toward the EUR 71,764 threshold.    - “Gross annual income” is
  measured for the calendar year preceding the year for which
  eligibility is assessed, and is taken before tax and before
  deduction of social security contributions.    - Do not include
  investment income or capital gains. (ECB Staff Rules, §3.5.1, p.63)
  3. Evidence and procedure:    - Provide evidence of income (for
  example, the latest tax declaration and salary statement, or other
  documents the ECB considers appropriate) to the ECB for assessment.
  (ECB Staff Rules, §3.5.2, p.63)  4. Related note:    - If both
  spouses are ECB staff and both earn less than the limit, the
  household allowance is paid to the staff member with the higher
  salary. (ECB Staff Rules, §3.5.4, p.63)  (ECB Staff Rules,
  §3.5.1–3.5.2, §3.5.4, p.63; ECB Conditions of Employment, p.9)
